- Bertrand Russell</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=grafireforgedawn>Grafire Forgedawn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/13/02 1:47:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=915.topic&index=32>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.inktank.com/images/eZgrafire.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_tongue.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: If you could make a fantasy book into a film, tv show, e</span><hr size=1> My vote goes towards bringing the Black Company series (by Glen Cook) come to life. I love those books.<br>
<br>
And on a side note, a friend of mine created an Amber roleplaying game (years before the official one came out) and we did art for the cards and all. The jist of the game was we all played princes and had to walk the pattern (path? it's been a few years) and go somewhere and train up an army to bring back. The no gun powder rule still applied though. Some guys spent months culling over history books and picking Roman Legions, Huns, Samauri, etc. One guy even found reference to air powered rifles and equiped his army with those.<br>
<br>
Who won?<br>
<br>
Why I did of course with my army of cartoon characters. (hey, it's Amber were talking about here) Nigh invulnerable to physical attacks (shot by cannon? Got a big hole in thier center, but can still fight. Hit by a war hammer? All acordianed up, but can still fight...etc.)<br>
<br>
The Amber world was great because of the open endedness of it. It's so expansive and truly, almost anything is possible.<br>
<br>
It's almost too open ended and limitless to really make a graphical adventure out of, but it would be cool to see on the big screen. But the budget would have to be huge. <p>-----------------<br>
